	<h2 id="motivation" class="vf-u-margin--0 vf-u-padding__top--400 vf-u-padding__bottom--600">Motivation</h2>
	<p>
		The Low Resource Optimisation (LRO) Framework originates from EMBL-EBI’s Global Engagement (GE) programme, which aims to make life science data services more accessible and inclusive, particularly for users in low-resource environments such as low-bandwidth settings.
	</p>
	<p>
		The Global Engagement (GE) programme aims to improve user experience (e.g. performance, accessibility, and visibility of EMBL-EBI web resources) by addressing key technical, infrastructural, and UX challenges, such as <strong>poor responsiveness, inaccessibility, and slow page load times</strong>, often caused by limited bandwidth, device constraints, and inadequate technical architecture and design considerations. 
	</p>
	<p>
		Addressing these challenges is critical to improving user experience and ensuring equitable access to EMBL-EBI services. Optimising for low-resource environments will expand global reach, improve usability, and help reduce the digital divide.
	</p>

	<h2 id="background" class="vf-u-margin--0 vf-u-padding__top--400 vf-u-padding__bottom--600">Background</h2>
	<p>
		The EMBL-EBI Global Engagement (GE) programme, funded by the Wellcome Trust, aims to explore new ways and data types needed to make biodata truly global by increasing biodata reuse.
	</p>
	<p>
		The programme aims to understand the current and future biodata needs of users in resource-constrained environments and respond through targeted interventions across four key workstreams:
	</p>
	<ul class="vf-list vf-list--unordered">
		<li class="vf-list__item">Listening and awareness</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Improving user experience</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Enabling data and infrastructure delivery</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Programme delivery, communication, and monitoring</li>
	</ul>
	<p>
		These efforts position EMBL-EBI to better support diverse global users and ensure its services remain accessible and relevant.
	</p>

	<h2 id="introduction-to-lro-framework" class="vf-u-margin--0 vf-u-padding__top--400 vf-u-padding__bottom--600">Introduction to LRO Framework</h2>
	<p>
		The Low Resource Optimisation (LRO) Framework provides a structured set of principles, guidelines, and best practices for designing, developing, and operating web services that remain accessible and usable in low-resource environments.
	</p>

	<h3 id="objectives">Objectives</h3>
	<p>The framework aims to:</p>
	<ul class="vf-list vf-list--unordered">
		<li class="vf-list__item">
			Define low-resource environments
			Establish a shared understanding of constraints, such as limited bandwidth, low-end devices, unstable connectivity, and high data costs.
		</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">
			Standardise design and engineering practices
			Provide clear guidance on frontend, backend, and content strategies that prioritise performance, resilience, and accessibility.
		</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">
			Enable consistent user experience:
			Ensure core content and functionality remain available regardless of network or device limitations.
		</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">
			Support scalable and sustainable delivery:
			Encourage efficient use of resources, reducing both operational cost and environmental impact.
		</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">
			Provide measurable benchmarks:
			Define performance thresholds, metrics, and testing approaches to assess LRO compliance.
		</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">
			Guide decision-making:
			Help teams choose appropriate architectures, technologies, and interaction models based on user context and constraints. 
		</li>
	</ul>

	<h2 id="look-ahead" class="vf-u-margin--0 vf-u-padding__top--400 vf-u-padding__bottom--600">LRO framework beyond web services: Look ahead</h2>
	<p>
		In this framework, Low Resource Optimisation (LRO) is often approached from a web performance perspective, focusing on improving accessibility and usability under constrained network and device conditions. However, for EMBL-EBI services, user challenges extend far beyond the web interface. Users interact with a broader ecosystem that includes data access, APIs, analysis tools, and submission workflows, all of which are affected by constraints such as connectivity, data scale, compute capacity, and infrastructure limitations.
	</p>
	<p>
		To provide a more complete view, this document extends LRO beyond web services, outlining the broader set of challenges across the full data lifecycle and highlighting where additional improvements are needed to support users in low-resource environments.
	</p>
